{"title":"RED-ACE: Robust Error Detection for ASR using Confidence Embeddings","domain":"SPEECH","seeds":[{"problem":"ASR error detection models typically rely only on the transcription text and ignore auxiliary ASR signals like word-level confidences, limiting their ability to accurately flag recognition errors.","method":"Introduce RED-ACE, a BERT-based sequence tagger augmented with a confidence embedding layer. ASR word-level confidence scores are quantized into bins and mapped via a learned embedding matrix; the confidence embedding is summed with the token, segment, and position embeddings to form each token’s input. This joint, contextualized encoding of text and confidence yields statistically significant F1 gains over text-only BERT and over naive score fusion (e.g., appending raw scores, BERT C) on LibriSpeech clean/other (e.g., +4.9% and +7.4% F1), remains robust under cross-pool shifts (+6.3% and +9.9% F1), and generalizes across different ASR models (+2.6% and +3.8% F1)."},{"problem":"There is a lack of publicly available, reproducible AED datasets with ASR outputs, word-level confidences, and error annotations; reliance on paid cloud ASR systems also hampers comparability as models evolve.","method":"Create and release a novel AED dataset by transcribing the LibriSpeech corpus with Google Cloud Speech-to-Text (default and video models), recording hypotheses and word-level confidences, and aligning hypotheses to references via minimum edit distance to label each word as ERROR/NOTERROR. The dataset includes both clean and other pools with detailed statistics and supports reproducible training/evaluation independent of cloud ASR availability or changes."}]}
